english:
  title: Record of the Flowing Sands Pavilion
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Flowing Sands—that desolate realm recorded in the Tributes of Yu, where the sage-king's teachings barely reach. Yet why one would name a pavilion after such a place, I confess I do not understand.

    When the ancients inscribed plaques for their retreats and resting grounds, they would choose names of renowned mountains and waters, or display great virtues and great vices to convey moral instruction, or commemorate the ancestral villages of old to preserve remembrance. But the Flowing Sands—that remote and wretched border, where no worthy person emerges, where neither boat nor carriage ventures—men speak of it with distaste and call upon it only in shame. How could any soul dare to carve such a name in grand characters upon a gate?

    Yet I know my brother's intention must surpass the ordinary. Consider this: Heaven's vastness and the sage's transformative influence extend without end—yet this is but the outer realm. But the body is small, the world immense, and they are one—this is the inner realm. From without, one sees teachings radiating from east to the Mulberry Tree, west to Kunlun, north to barren wastes, south to lands of no snow. The sage's grace spreads gradually, yet unity remains rare while division endless—how can this not weigh upon my heart? From within, though sinew and bone bind us, though emotion and nature are fleeting, the heart encompasses the cosmos, responds to all things, cannot be moved by force nor hindered by cunning. What grand sovereignty this one self possesses! Thus even one concealed in a remote corner, quiet and hidden away, carries within his breast a measure that the sage's transformation reaches across all distant quarters—nothing lies beyond it.

    Is this not your intention, brother?

    Once I too harbored ambitions to wander far and wide. Now I am weary. In the winter of Xinyin, fleeing the turmoil of war, I journeyed east and at last reached Ninghai prefecture—my mother's home, where my brother dwells. Ninghai faces the great sea to the east, with Japan as neighbor; truly it is the far extreme of our Eastern Kingdom. By fortune I have reached this corner and glimpsed its uttermost point. From here, all else may be understood in reverse. How much more so regarding the Flowing Sands that lies opposite?

    Raising cup upon this pavilion, my brother requested this record. With gladness I write it.

    Zhizheng, year of Renyin.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Tributes of Yu (Yugong) is a classical Chinese geographical text describing the regions reached by Yu the Great's rule and teachings.
  - key: ''
    value: Mulberry Tree (Fusang) and Kunlun represent the eastern and western extremes of the known world in classical Chinese cosmography.
  - key: ''
    value: Ninghai prefecture is located in present-day Gangneung, Kangwon Province, on Korea's east coast.
  - key: ''
    value: The year Xinyin corresponds to 1371 CE; Zhizheng year Renyin corresponds to 1392 CE, suggesting this record was written some twenty years after the events described.
